accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays in Nationalizing Empires challenge the dichotomy between empire and nation state that for decades has dominated historiography. The authors center their attention on nation-building in the imperial core and maintain that the nineteenth century, rather than the age of nation-states, was the age of empires and nationalism. They identify a number of instances where nation building projects in the imperial metropolis aimed at the preservation and extension of empires rather than at their dissolution or the transformation of entire empires into nation states. Such observations have until recently largely escaped theoretical reflection.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aImperialismxHistoryy19th century. 0aMilitary history, Moderny19th century. 0aNation-buildingxHistoryy19th century. 0aNation-statexHistoryy19th century. 0aNationalismxHistoryy19th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Nationalism & Patriotism.2bisacsh  aForeign relations, History, Modernization, Nation-building, Nation-state, Nationalism, World War I.1 aAldrich, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Stefan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBroers, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamien, Elsa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEissenstat, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomlosy, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaven, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeonhard, Jö